Lecture: Handling Alerts in Selenium (Java)

1. Introduction
- In web applications, sometimes a popup message box (alert) appears.
- Alerts interrupt the normal flow of execution until the user interacts with them.
- Selenium provides the Alert interface to handle these popups.

Think of alerts as a security guard at the hostel gate. Until you respond (OK, Cancel, or give input),
you cannot move forward.


2. Types of Alerts
- Simple Alert → Just shows a message with an OK button.
- Confirmation Alert → Asks for confirmation with OK and Cancel.
- Prompt Alert → Asks the user to enter text before proceeding.

3. Steps to Handle Alerts
- Switch to the alert
Alert alert = driver.switchTo().alert();
- Perform actions
- alert.accept(); → Clicks OK.
- alert.dismiss(); → Clicks Cancel.
- alert.getText(); → Gets the alert message.
- alert.sendKeys("text"); → Enters text into a prompt alert.

Examples
Example 1: Simple Alert
Alert alert = driver.switchTo().alert();
System.out.println(alert.getText());  // print alert message
alert.accept();                       // click OK


Example 2: Confirmation Alert
Alert alert = driver.switchTo().alert();
alert.dismiss();   // click Cancel


Example 3: Prompt Alert
Alert alert = driver.switchTo().alert();
alert.sendKeys("Test");  // enter text
alert.accept();               // click OK

5. Best Practices
- Always wait for the alert before switching (use WebDriverWait).
- Handle unexpected alerts with try–catch to avoid test failures.
- Close alerts immediately to continue test execution.



Handling Alerts in Selenium
│
├── Switch to Alert → driver.switchTo().alert()
│
├── Actions
│   ├── accept() → OK
│   ├── dismiss() → Cancel
│   ├── getText() → Read message
│   └── sendKeys() → Enter text (Prompt)
│
└── Best Practices
    ├── Use WebDriverWait
    ├── Handle unexpected alerts
    └── Close alerts quickly
